<h2>Solar Panels in Utah</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>

<p>Utah's solar irradiance levels consistently rank among the highest in the nation, with most regions receiving between 4.8 and 5.8 peak sun hours daily on average. The state benefits from exceptional solar conditions due to its high elevation (average 6,100 feet above sea level), low annual precipitation (typically 12-16 inches), and consistently clear skies. Northern Utah, including the Wasatch Front metropolitan areas, receives approximately 5.1-5.4 peak sun hours daily, while southern Utah near St. George and Moab can exceed 5.8 peak sun hours, rivaling Arizona's solar potential.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations in Utah create interesting production patterns that align well with energy consumption needs. Summer months (June through August) typically produce 140-160% of average monthly output, with July peak production often reaching 180% of the annual average. Winter production drops to approximately 60-70% of the annual average, but snow typically melts quickly due to steep roof angles and intense high-altitude sunlight. Spring and fall months provide consistent production at 90-110% of average, creating excellent shoulder season performance that helps offset seasonal HVAC demands.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in Utah ranges from 5kW to 12kW, with the average 7kW system producing approximately 10,500-11,500 kWh annually. This production level can offset 80-120% of a typical Utah home's electricity consumption, depending on energy efficiency measures and HVAC system performance. Utah's net metering policies allow excess production to be credited at full retail rates, making oversized systems economically attractive for homes with high cooling loads or electric heating systems.</p>

