<h2>Utah Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Utah offers a comprehensive suite of incentives that make solar and HVAC investments highly attractive for homeowners. The foundation of these incentives begins with the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations through 2032. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work. For a typical \$25,000 solar installation, homeowners can claim a \$7,500 federal tax credit, significantly reducing the effective system cost.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The 30% federal tax credit remains the most significant incentive available to Utah homeowners. This credit covers the full cost of solar panel systems, including equipment, installation, permits, and interconnection fees. Unlike rebates, tax credits reduce your federal tax liability dollar-for-dollar, and unused credits can be carried forward to future tax years. The credit is scheduled to decrease to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations.</li>

<li><strong>Utah State Renewable Energy Tax Credit:</strong> Utah offers a state tax credit equal to 25% of the cost of renewable energy systems, up to a maximum of \$1,600 for residential installations. This credit can be combined with the federal ITC, providing additional savings for Utah homeowners. The state credit applies to solar panels, solar water heating, geothermal systems, and qualifying wind installations.</li>

<li><strong>Rocky Mountain Power Solar Incentive Program:</strong> Rocky Mountain Power offers performance-based incentives for qualifying solar installations through their Schedule 135 net metering program. While direct cash incentives are limited, the utility provides full retail rate credit for excess solar production, effectively creating a 1:1 energy credit system. Additionally, Rocky Mountain Power offers time-of-use rates that can increase solar savings by 15-25% for homes with battery storage systems.</li>

<li><strong>Local Utility Programs:</strong> Several municipal utilities in Utah offer additional rebates and incentives. Salt Lake City Corporation provides rebates up to \$2,000 for solar installations and additional incentives for battery storage systems. Provo City offers similar programs with rebates up to \$1,500 for qualifying renewable energy systems. These local programs often have limited funding and operate on a first-come, first-served basis.</li>

<li><strong>HVAC Rebates and Incentives:</strong> Utah residents can access federal tax credits for qualifying heat pumps, geothermal systems, and high-efficiency HVAC equipment through the Inflation Reduction Act. Heat pump installations can qualify for up to \$2,000 in federal tax credits, while geothermal systems can receive 30% tax credits similar to solar installations. Rocky Mountain Power and Dominion Energy offer rebates ranging from \$200-800 for high-efficiency furnaces, air conditioners, and heat pumps that meet ENERGY STAR requirements.</li>
</ul>

